DOCS_modelChunk = [{"ty":"is","ibi":1,"s":"QCUSD School Closure & COVID-19 Family FAQ 
Updated April 20
***will be updated as needed***
***questions most recently updated are towards the beginning of the FAQ***

In an effort to support our families, we have provided the following Frequently Asked Questions. Please know this information is in effect from March 23 through the rest of the school year. 

Q: Are QCUSD schools closing?
Yes. Governor Doug Ducey announced the extension of Arizona school closures through the end of the 2019-2020 school year. This includes the Queen Creek Unified School District. (Governor’s announcement). The extension follows updated guidance from the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) and an announcement from the White House extending physical distancing guidelines.

MEALS
(NEW) Q: Can my child still get school meals during the closure?. 
Beginning Monday April 13, meal distribution will take place at Queen Creek High School and Eastmark High School.
Meals will no longer be handed out at the QC Boys and Girls Club
Meals are handed out via a curbside grab and go model
Meals are free for children 18 and under
Delivery time is still 10am-12pm. 


REMOTE LEARNING//TESTING
(UPDATED)Q: Will my child's grades be negatively impacted because of school closures and remote learning?
Students engaged in remote learning should not see overall grades go down based on school closures and the shift to remote learning. Teachers will be flexible and work with students to ensure that overall fourth quarter grades mirror overall third quarter grades or are enhanced during this time.
All grades that are added to the gradebook during school closures will be categorized as "not for scoring or "extra credit. This means that those scores will either keep the Q3 grades the same or it may enhance them.

(NEW) Q: What is the plan for our childrens' grade placement next year?
QCUSD continues to provide educational services to maintain the learning that was already happening in the classrooms. Your child will receive a final report card for their final grade and they will proceed into their next grade as planned. 


(NEW) Q: Will State testing still take place?
Governor Ducey signed legislation to help support school districts in the event of an extended closure. This support includes suspension of statewide testing requirements.
Per the school closure emergency legislation signed on March 27, 2020, Statewide assessments for 2019-2020 (AZM2, MSAA, AIMS Science, etc.) are cancelled.
On Tuesday, March 31, 2020, the U.S. Department of Education (ED) notified ADE that we have met all statutory requirements necessary to receive a federal waiver from testing and accountability.
(UPDATED) Q: Has summer school been canceled due to the closure?
We are currently planning to offer online summer school in leiu of traditional summer school. We will continue to monitor the situation as it evolves and communicate summer school opportunities to families.

Q: Will on-line instruction be available for QCUSD students?
Queen Creek Unified has been preparing for the possibility of extended closures and teachers will continue to provide educational services that build upon the learning that was occurring in the classroom. Google Classroom (K-8) and/or Edgenuity (9-12) will be the on-line platforms utilized by individual teachers or grade levels to provide on-line educational services and activities that are specific to a subject or class/course. See the following site for tutorials: 
QCUSD Home Support for Remote Learning

Q: Will families get guidance pertaining to remote learning? 
Yes, below is a link to a guide that lays out general guidelines and best practices regarding remote learning. Please email your child(s) teacher with any questions. They will be checking emails during their regular school hours.
QCUSD Remote Learning Site
Additional at-home educational enrichment resources
QCUSD Learning at Home Guide

Q: Will my student’s teacher be available for questions during school closures?
Teachers are required to be available during their normal contract hours during school closures. They will be answering emails and voicemails.
Q: Since schools are closed, will the school year be extended?
Students will not need to make up days missed due to the current school closure. 



SENIORS/HIGH SCHOOL/PERSONAL ITEMS
(NEW) Q: Will there be a time when students can go to school campuses to clean out desks/lockers?
Yes, individual schools sites will be communicating specific dates and times regarding when sites will be open to pick up personal items.


NEW) Q: What is the school and district doing to address high school graduation?
QCHS graduation plans are unknown at this time but Queen Creek High School and District Office staff is committed to affording students some sort of graduation ceremony if our pandemic situation improves and social distancing advisories are lifted.

NEW)Q: Will the closure impact my dual enrollment classes?
Students will need to complete the online work that will be provided by their Dual Enrollment teacher(s). Students must demonstrate minimum competencies/skills, as determined by the community college, to finish the semester and earn credit. Your child’s Dual Enrollment teacher will continue to work closely with students to provide support and information.

Q: Will my child receive their diploma at the graduation ceremony?
When your child has met the State Board of Education and QCUSD graduation requirements, they will be awarded their diploma.

Q: Will end of year school assemblies/events (Senior Awards, Prom, 8th grade activities, elementary award ceremonies, etc.) still take place? 
End of the year activities will not take place as originally planned due to the Governor’s decision to close all schools in Arizona until the end of the school year. As the situation continues to evolve, we will monitor closely. 

Q: What about QCUSD students who attend EVIT?
EVIT is closed until further notice.

Q: My child is joining the armed services right after graduation, and their diploma
 is required. What can we do?
The military representatives that work with Queen Creek High School have indicated they will be flexible and work with families as necessary due to school closures. Please contact the military representative working with your family to have your questions answered about how the school closure will impact your son or daughter’s enlistment date.

Q: Will the May SAT testing that is scheduled at QCHS still happen?
No, the College Board has cancelled the May SAT testing. The College Board will be refunding fees paid for registration. Please refer to the College Board website for more information. https://pages.collegeboard.org/natural-disasters

Q: How does the school closure affect Advanced Placement (AP) testing? 
As of March 16, 2020, the AP program is developing resources to help schools support student learning. SPECIAL EDUCATION

(NEW): Q: Is QCUSD required to continue to provide a free appropriate public education (FAPE) to students with disabilities during a school closure caused by a COVID-19 Outbreak?
	
For a temporary school closure, no, but this specific situation is very different. Until Monday, March 30th, school closures were temporary.
Your child’s Special Education teacher will be providing learning opportunities during the time of the school closure, beginning the week of March 30th. They will be communicating with students and parents during this time. Good faith efforts will be provided to each student to ensure that learning activities are adapted to each student's needs, and that they are targeted toward goal areas.
Related service providers, such as Speech, Occupational Therapy, Counseling, Physical Therapy, Hearing services, or Visual impairment services, will also be communicating with you to provide meaningful targeted activities directly related to established IEP goals.
As instructional resources are made available to all students those resources will be adapted and modified for special education students so they have equal access and opportunities. 

Q. Do Special Education timelines apply during the COVID-19 outbreak, such as annual IEP due dates and Evaluation timelines?
Yes, all Special Education timelines still apply during the COVID-19 outbreak. The US Department of Education has encouraged all schools to work with parents and reach mutually agreeable extensions of time, as appropriate, but clarify that all timelines are still in effect. In the event that parents have concerns with in-person testing or screenings to meet timelines, QCUSD will work with parents on individual cases to stop evaluations and resume when school is back in regular session.


ATHLETICS
Q: Will Queen Creek High School & Eastmark High School athletics continue with the district being closed?
No, during the time that schools are closed all athletic competitions, practices, tryouts, and workouts for Queen Creek High School and Eastmark High School will be canceled. This is for the rest of the school year. Here is a link from the Arizona Interscholastic Association with more information about athletic programs during closures: https://www.azpreps365.com/coronavirus

Q: Will the NBMS and QCMS middle school athletics continue with the district being closed?
No, during the time that schools are closed all athletic competitions, practices, tryouts, and workouts for Newell Barney Middle School and Queen Creek Middle School are canceled. 

REFUNDS AND FIELD TRIPS

NEW Q: Where can I get information on refunds for athletic fees, lunch money or other fees?
Request a refund by following the process outlined here.



Q: Will school field trips take place as scheduled during school closures? 
No. All previously planned field trips are cancelled. If you paid for a field trip set to take place during the closure or that is cancelled, we will be flexible with refund options. 


CHILDCARE
(NEW) Q: Will childcare be available while schools are closed?
QCUSD childcare will be available through Thursday, April 9. For alternatives in our area or nearby click on the links below:
Governor letter on emergency child care
https://arizonaenrichmentcenters.az.gov/find-care 
https://azafterschool.org/family-resources-child-care-options/ 


Q: How will the closure impact TOYBOX?
TOYBOX follows the school calendar and will also be closed. Tuition will not be charged during school closure. Changes to this will be communicated to TOYBOX parents. 

Q: Will QCUSD Preschool programs continue during school closures?
No. Preschool programs, TOYBOX included, will not continue during a closure. Parents will not pay for those days. However, there are options available for childcare, if needed. Please email qcpre@qcusd.org for information.
 

OTHER

(NEW) Q: How do I enroll for the 20-21 school year?
You can enroll your student by printing off an enrollment packet from our website (https://www.qcusd.org/Registration), fill the packet out, then scan and email the packet back to the registrar for the school you wish to enroll your child in. Only new families/new enrollees need to do this.

(UPDATED) Q: Will Student Council, Site Council, and Booster/PTO Elections for 20-21 boards/committees occur during the closure as typical in normal years?
At this time, all elections will be suspended to ensure equity and transparency for all involved. This is a difficult time for individuals and families and focus should be on student and family wellness and continued student learning during closure. 



(NEW) Q: Will school and district community events (i.e. carnivals, concerts, career days, Business Partner Breakfast, Parent Institute classes, CAFE, Awards of Excellence Dinner, etc.) continue as scheduled?
All school and district group activities through the end of the 2019-2020 school year have been cancelled. 

Q: Will adult education classes continue when schools are closed?
Adult education classes will be closed when schools are closed. 

Q: Will school facilities continue to be rented?
All rentals of our buildings to outside groups are suspended until further notice.

Q: Why did Queen Creek Unified School District close all schools?
QCUSD has been actively monitoring COVID-19 coronavirus and following the recommendations from Governor Doug Ducey’s Office, the Arizona Department of Health, and the Arizona Department of Education. 
Q: Are there any coronavirus cases in QCUSD?
There are no known cases of COVID-19 at any Queen Creek Unified School District campus or site.

Q: What can students, families, and staff do?
Be aware of symptoms of illness and stay home if you are not feeling well. Follow best practices for prevention of the spread of viruses, including COVID - 19 and the common cold or flu. Respect the privacy of students and staff, and take steps to prevent discrimination. Ensure contact information is up-to-date in the event that large group notifications are sent by phone, email, and text message. Keep yourself up-to-date on what the Maricopa County Health Department, the Arizona Department of Health Services and the Centers for Disease Control (CDC) suggest.

Q: What precautions has QCUSD taken to date?
Queen Creek has followed strict guidelines from the CDC, Arizona Department of Health, and Maricopa County of Health when it comes to precautions. All QCUSD facilities are and will continue to be fully sanitized and thoroughly deep cleaned. QCUSD had been taking proactive measures prior to this event by enhancing its cleaning protocols and have implemented additional decontamination measures over Spring Break. We are also ensuring that soap and hand sanitizer are available throughout the district. 

Q: How are you handling individuals (students and staff) who have traveled to areas with a high number of cases?
QCUSD has adopted recommendations from the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention regarding travel to high risk areas. The CDC is asking individuals who traveled to an area with widespread, ongoing community spread (Level 3 Travel Health Notice countries) to stay home for 14 days from the time you left that area. Click this link to find out which countries have a Level 3 Travel Health Notice (widespread, ongoing transmission)


Q: How often will I receive communication/updates? 
You can expect frequent communication during the school closure. We will send updates via email and post on our website as well as district social media. Please also make sure you continue to check the FAQ link for updates. 

Q: Do I need to report my child as absent during the closure of schools?
No. Parents will not need to report their child’s absence during a school closure.



Q: How will Governing Board meetings take place during school closures?
Per ASBA legal guidance, Board meetings will be closed to the public during school closures but they are available to view via livestream on the QCUSD YouTube channel. Meetings will follow the regular format, however, public comments can be sent via email to qnelson@qcusd.org.

Q: My question isn't listed here. How can I ask a question?
QCUSD staff is working to answer the most frequently asked parent questions and will update this page as often as necessary. You can also email questions to covidquestions@qcusd.org.

Additional resources for families:

Social & Emotional Resources for Families


For individual health concerns, please contact your healthcare provider or call the designated Arizona Department of Public Health Coronavirus Hotline at 1-844-542-8201.

There is a new statewide hotline that residents can call with questions related to COVID-19. It is available in both English and Spanish, and can be reached by dialing 2-1-1 from 8:00 a.m. to 8:00 p.m. The hotline will provide information on:
 
· how to prepare for and prevent the spread of COVID-19;
· testing for COVID-19 as it becomes available;
· who is at a higher risk of contracting COVID-19;
· what to do if you get sick; and
· where to find the most up-to-date and accurate information (e.g., the CDC).
